cp|8|fp||at|^c@2^Y@3Kia|CP||AT| - I understand DONT stands for (D)isturb (O)pponents (N)o (T)rump and Marty Bergen is the author. Please explain it and tell us when is it used?|
PG| ***** 1 ***** |


cp|8|AT|

Howard: ^*N|cp||at|DONT should be used when you have a hand suitable for competing over a 1N opener. I will discuss the exact requirements later. But, in general, if your hand is either somewhat distributional or has some strength, you should compete by making a DONT bid.
|
pg| ***** 2 ***** |


cp|8|fp||at|^c@2^Y@3Kia|CP||AT| - Is it correct that DONT is really to disturb and get a part score rather than trying for a game or higher auctions?|
PG| ***** 3 ***** |


cp|8|AT|

Howard: ^*N|cp||at|Yes, the purpose of DONT is to arrive at the best part score. In general, once an opponent opens a strong NT, it is unlikely your side has game. So, DONT is designed to get you to a good part score. You may occasionally miss a game, but this is more than made up by the many successful part scores you will find if you play DONT.
|
pg| ***** 4 ***** |


cp|8|fp||at|^c@2^Y@3Kia|CP||AT| - There are other conventions to disturb a 1NT opener beside DONT such as Astro, Pinpoint, Brozel, Modified Brozel, Hamilton, Cappiletti and Modified Cappiletti. You do prefer DONT. What is your reasoning? |
PG| ***** 5 ***** |


cp|8|AT|

Howard: ^*N|cp||at|I prefer DONT because it allows you to compete on more hand types and find a good part score at the 2 level. Most of these other conventions often require stronger hands to compete because you may often end up at the 3 level, so you will have to pass with many hands that, were you playing DONT, you would be able to compete with.
|
