cp|8|fp||at|^c@2^Y@3Kia|CP||AT| - Another good teacher opines that the auction of 1NT-P-P-P is difficult to successfully defend and the intention for opponent should be to push them out of 1NT auction. What are your thoughts on the issue please?|
PG| ***** 7 ***** |


cp|8|AT|^^
Howard: ^*N|cp||at|I agree with the other teacher that more often than not, you will not get a good score if the auction goes 1N-P-P-P. At best, you are unlikely to beat 1N more than a trick or two, and if you can beat it, you probably can make a part score of your own. And, they will often make 1N, and you will still have a part score contract that you could have made instead.|
pg| ***** 8 ***** |


cp|8|fp||at|
^c@2^Y@3Kia|CP||AT| - Is it true that DONT is really more so based on shape rather the points of the hand? I will ask specifics later.|
PG| ***** 9 ***** |


cp|8|AT|
Howard: ^*N|cp||at|The more distribution you have, the fewer points you need to bid DONT. And, because the NT opener has a good hand, on average you will hold fewer points. So, because of that, you will tend to compete more often with DONT based on distribution than high cards.
|
pg| ***** 10 ***** |


cp|8|fp||at|^c@2^Y@3Kia|CP||AT| - Now then, my RHO opens 1NT. What should I look for in my hand to correctly bid a DONT. Now, you can be specific with shape and point range please.|
PG| ***** 11 ***** |


cp|8|AT|
Howard: ^*N|cp||at|Let us look at single suited hands first. You should bid DONT if you have the same sort of hand that you would be willing to overcall with a suit at the 2 level had the opponent opened a suit at the one level. So, you need either a six card suit, or a good five card suit, and typically at least ten or so points (using Bergen hand evaluation methods).|
PG| ***** 12 ***** |


AT|

With a 2 suited hand, it is a bit more complicated. With 5/5, you can compete with as few as 7 or 8 HCP, particularly if your values are concentrated in your suits. With 5/4, you probably should have at least 10 or 11 HCP. Lately, I almost never bid DONT in direct seat with only 4-4 and will only bid DONT in balancing seat with 4-4 if I have close to an opener and my 2 suits are very good (each have at least 2 honors).|
PG| ***** 13 ***** |


AT|

Also, you should be a bit more cautious when you are vulnerable, and can be a bit more aggressive when non-vulnerable.
|
